        <h1>LeetCode 1611: Minimum One Bit Operations to Make Integers Zero (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                Given an integer n, you must transform it into 0 using the minimum number of operations. In each
                operation,
                you can change the rightmost (0th) bit in the binary representation of n, or change the ith bit in the
                binary representation of n if the (i-1)th bit is set to 1 and the (i-2)th through 0th bits are set to 0.
                Return the minimum number of operations to make n equal to 0.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: n = 3 → Output: 2. The binary representation of 3 is "11". Apply operation on the 0th bit: "11" →
                "10".
                Apply operation on the 1st bit: "10" → "00". Total operations = 2.
                Input: n = 6 → Output: 4. Binary "110" requires 4 operations to reach "000".
                Input: n = 9 → Output: 14. Binary "1001" requires 14 operations.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minimumOneBitOperations(int n) {
        // Base: 0 already needs no operations
        if (n == 0)
            return 0;
        // Find highest power of 2 ≤ n
        int p = 1;
        while (p &lt;&lt; 1 &lt;= n)
            p &lt;&lt;= 1;
        // Flip the highest bit (1XXX → 1100 pattern)
        // Recursively solve for remaining bits using XOR
        // Formula: total = steps to flip + remaining ops + lower group cost
        return minimumOneBitOperations(n ^ (p | (p &gt;&gt; 1))) + p;
    }
};</code></pre>
